ope and love that are central to radical acts of resistance to oppression. Themes range from critical literacies to IQ tests, from Afro-surrealism to historiography, as the book strategically tacks between traditional forms of qualitative and quantitative research and more personal narratives. Black Lives Matter in US Schools speaks powerfully against the continued onslaught of inequities in schools and their communities, working to create space for forms of learning that are responsible to and for Black lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAfrican AmericansxEducation. 0aBlack lives matter movementzUnited States. 0aEducationxCurriculaxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aEducational equalizationzUnited States. 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 4aEducation : Education. 4aEducation : Social Context of Education. 4aGender and Sexuality : Queer Studies. 4aSociology : Social Movements. 7aEDUCATION / Curricula.2bisacsh1 aBaszile, Denise Taliaferro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdwards, Kirsten T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGershon, Walter S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaddix, Marcelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHughes, Sherick A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLavache, Cluny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMitchell, Reagan P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMitchell, Roland W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSealey-Ruiz, Yolanda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSpence, Lester K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators